Voreverl awakens… somewhere. Some vaguely suburban neighborhood, on a bench.

Voreverl takes a moment to adjust to the suddenness of the scenery change, especially after the recent rush of emotions and revelations. She clenches her hands a few times, feeling the sensation of returning to her body after the unusually long time away. After getting her bearings, she sits up straight on the bench and scans the area for life.

There’s two people standing around on the sidewalk. One of them looks at you briefly.

Voreverl’s cellphone rings.
With a reaction speed notably slower than that which would serve to protect an evil empire, Voreverl reaches to grab her phone and check the number.
It’s Meryl.

Voreverl's head feels just about ready to burst open, her grip on her phone just barely enough to keep from dropping it. She takes a deep breath, and slaps herself across the face as hard as she can. At the top of her lungs, she releases a declaration.

"I AM VOREVERL LEOCOT! I SHALL HAVE MY REVENGE! ALL WHO OPPOSE ME SHALL FALL! GWEHAHAHAHAH!" She answers the phone immediately after finishing this battle cry "Ms. Leiblich, it's been a while. For what reason do you interrupt my machinations? Spit it out!"
A sigh can be heard on the other end. "*Why am I so....* Yes, hello. It's you. I guess he got the timing right. I don't need this to be a drawn out thing, just a yes or no answer."

Voreverl takes a moment to respond, having to force the words up and out of her throat "...No! That's... I am ordering you to stay on the line for longer! I... am in need of information! You shall be a valuable non-renewable resource, with which I shall pollute the hopes of my ignorance that my enemies hold!"

"The next transfer is the last one. You'll go to Arctica, whatever nonsense happens there will happen, and then you'll come back. And the project will be over. There's your info. I don't have the ability to stop it, but it won't be very long regardless."
"That... Indeed! My sheer intimidation was enough to torture what I needed out of you! You are quite crafty to know to avoid a confrontation with the likes of Voreverl Leocot!"

"Unfortunately not. It should be over by two weeks from now, is the point. I..."

She pauses. "...Do you know? About your father..."
Voreverl does not respond, not a single word comes to mind for her to even blurt out. Her breathing begins to speed up, coming in uneven clumps rather than a steady pace.
"...Sorry." Meryl Leiblich does not come up with any other words to say.

It's a struggle to speak at this point, but Voreverl gathers up enough strength to manage "...Why are you apologizing? This is great news... My enemy is... I'm happy about this! Why wouldn't I be!? He's not even my father! I have no father! Good riddance, you bastard!"

The other end is silent for a few seconds before some undiscernible non-word noises. Crying... or laughter.
"Yes, so it goes... only I seem to remember anything... that's funny. Uuu. I agonized over what to do, but believed I'd regret it if I didn't even attempt to reach out about the funeral. Just to hear the 'no' myself. If you showed up, though, you'd just make a scene, wouldn't you? Maybe that's only right. You two deserve each other. I'm sure eeevveryone's satisfied with this outcome, then. *I'm not!*"

"..." Voreverl slowly begins to stand up, and upon completion, she starts pacing back and forth in front of the bench, taking in a deep breath before responding "...I could infiltrate the funeral. If it's for reconnaissance, Voreverl Leocot wouldn't need to make a scene."

"Yeah, yeah, that's fine. It's all fine if the result is okay. Right? I've been able to keep myself going with that for years. Talk is talk. It shouldn't matter what people present as, it's the modern world, takes all kinds. I mean, what do I care? What's the worst that could happen? You pull some insane stunt at an event to solemnly honor the memory of a dead man, he certainly won't be around to mind. What's it to me? Hey, did you know I don't have anything left but you? It's true! I gave up my career to start a family. I'd do it again! I don't regret choosing to be a human over a researcher! My social circle dissolved entirely when I became the mother of an international criminal, but I know that was just testing me, right? You need to hold onto what's most important as tight as you can, right? So it's okay. This is why we have faith. Because we need some way to believe things will work out, even when logic can't bring us there. There's a lot of things that are important that we only achieve through belief."

"Mom, I..." Voreverl moves her hand to slap herself once again, but stops short, and just stands there for a moment. Tears begins to well before she can say anything "...I'm sorry... I'm sorry! I'm sorry! I'm sorry! It's all my fault! I... I left him alone with them! I could have stopped them! Voreverl Leocot could have! But... but now he's... and I can never take it back! I can't take any of it back!" Her eyes have stopped acting as wells for the tears, and instead serve as a hose for them to pour out of. Her nose does much the same. If Meryl could see her, Voreverl would appear as nothing but a disheveled mess.

She trips over her own words, desperate to say something yet unable to grasp what it is. “Wh… um, oh, I… no, no it isn’t! There… I don’t even understand it yet, but he knew he was heading down a dangerous road. You were just trying to get by in a world he was tearing apart! And I knew… I knew him, what his problem was. I should have done something. I don’t know. I hate— th-that the last thing I said to him was about divorce. I don’t think I could’ve gone through with it. I just wanted to scare him. I thought…! I thought I could be the one to bring him to his senses. If I had called him out sooner, I might… Maybe… someone does need to be the bad guy sometimes.”

"No... No!" She shakes her head furiously "You're just a minion, you couldn't do anything! He wouldn't listen to someone like you! This was between important people... real villains! I had the manpower... I could have had an army! I could have stormed that fucking pizzeria and stopped everything! But I screwed it up! I lost it! I killed dad just like I killed Eric!"
“We’re only human…” She mutters, vaguely confused.

"I'm... I'm not! Voreverl Leocot is a god! And... and Jane Leiblich is just... just an Arctican... I'm not even real, am I? I've just been playing pretend my whole life! You should have just let me die! At least then I'd be living as myself and not *this*!"

“No! No. I refuse. I’m not going to play coy, or see if it’s a phase, or throw my hands in the air and wait. This is where I stand for something. If there was ever a good decision I’ve made in my life, it was that one. I don’t know if… he was your father or not. It’s a messy ordeal. But you’re my daughter. Whoever or whatever you are. I don’t care if you came from magic, or some machine, or some alien planet. It doesn’t matter at all.”

Voreverl falls to her knees and begins sobbing uncontrollably. Through the cries and wails of all her pent up emotional baggage coming to the surface at once, sounds vaguely resembling two words can be made out.

"...thank... you..."
“I’ll… call you back later. I need to, um, check some… things…”
She hangs up.
Voreverl drops her phone and just holds her head in her hands, continuing to release screams and cries until she runs out of breath and feels her throat begin to tear.
Someone approaches her, standing silently in front of Voreverl Leocot. It’s one of the two people she originally saw standing around.

Voreverl Leocot, without a second thought, springs to her feet. Even if there weren't tears in her eyes, she would not take a moment to check who this person is. Before she can even realize what she's doing, she tightly embraces them.
They freeze up, startled, then half-return the gesture, patting her on the back.
After a few seconds, Voreverl realizes what she's doing, and breaks it off. She tries to sputter something out, and after a couple attempts, ends up with a "...S-sorry..."
“It’s fine. There’s been much weirder.”

Voreverl wipes her face off with her sleeve to try to appear a bit more presentable "...Weird? Gwehah! As if I'd be concerned with that! You and your puny mind have fallen hook, line, and sinker for my textbook manipulation tactics! Witness the power of Voreverl Leocot's deception!"

“Do you think it will work? I personally think that method of obfuscating true motivations is a bit overplayed. Unless you’re able to forge compelling evidence that you were actually acting with ulterior motive, it’s hard to believe that people believe it.”

She crosses her arms and looks away "A wise guy, huh? I'll have you know that I've successfully pushed away everyone in my life by informing them of my evil intentions! It's natural instinct to run in the opposite direction of a being of pure malice!"
“It sounds as if you are terrible at manipulation, then.” They smile.

"That's... Voreverl Leocot is amazing at manipulation! The only reason you think that I'm not is that I'm tricking you into underestimating me! So just... leave me alone. You're not even worth considering wasting my time on, considering how easy it was to play you right into my hand."
“Are you certain you want to be alone?” The person’s expression takes on a variety of forms very quickly. “I think you are not capable of existing in isolation.”

"Not capable!? I'm... I'm capable of anything!" She points an accusatory finger "You're the one who's incapable of understanding my machinations! So just forget what you saw here! Keep your head down and your mouth shut about what you saw me doing, got it? This is a threat!"

“Oh, absolutely. It would mess things up if anyone important really understood that side of you, is my understanding. The secret’s safe. But I can’t very well leave you alone until I know things are in place.”
"...What? Are you-" Her eyes dart up and down the person in front of her "Are you not just a random passerby? Are you... with The Antarctica Project?"

“Eh… not really. I guess it depends. There’s a lot of different things that phrase refers to.” They gesture to the second person standing in the immediate vicinity. “That woman over there is irrelevant and heard and saw nothing, by the way. She barely knows what’s going on, really. Don’t worry about that part.”
"That explains nothing! Well, the part about the woman is helpful, but... ugh. Just tell me if I need to kill you to get my revenge or not."
“Oh, revenge? That part’s easy. Everyone you’re looking for is in there.” They point to one of the nearby houses.

Voreverl stares at them, and just looks back and forth between the house and the person in front of them a few times "This... isn't a trap, right? Like, if I told someone that, I'd definitely be sending them to a death trap. I don't particularly *care* why they're here, but... the universe is supposed to be against me, Voreverl Leocot."

“Please. I’m an author. I don’t do bias. The ‘universe’ I know seems to be fond of you, though.”
I wouldn’t put it like that.
“Anyway, I’m not going to pretend you’ll be guaranteed fine. At least one of the clusterfuck of people in there might want to kick your ass. I just think it would be inconsistent for you to shrink away with that knowledge.”

A smirk forms on Voreverl's face "Kick *my* ass? Not likely! Let them come at Voreverl Leocot! Whether this is a death trap or you really have my enemies gathered there, I'll come out on top all the same! If the universe is fond of me, I'll show it why it should fear me instead!" Voreverl breaks out into a sprint towards the house.
